http://news.bbc.co.uk/go/rss/-/1/hi/england/hereford/worcs/6709125.stm | Shropshire | Police introduce new head cameras GMT 17:35 introduce new head cameras The equipment attaches to a headband worn under a helmet Police in Herefordshire are introducing state-of-the-art head camera technology to deter crime and disorder. The equipment, which is attached to a headband worn under a helmet, allows officers to film on patrol. Six head cams will be used, with each camera kit costing about £900. The equipment is also being trialled in Telford and Wrekin in Shropshire. There is a screen so officers can see who did what in public disorder situations, West Mercia police said. In many cases this will come as a wake up call Each camera kit can record up to 160 hours of images. Offenders can also be shown their behaviour. Footage can also be transferred to a computer or projector at a police station and every recorded frame cannot be tampered with, police said. Images can be used to help to provide evidence for the courts. Officers in Hereford are the first to be trained to use the new equipment in the county, but the cameras will be rolled out across Herefordshire in the coming months. Supt Adam Thomas, from Herefordshire Division, said: "The head cams will be used to film anti-social behaviour, alcohol-related disorder and other offences witnessed by officers as they go about their patrols in our town and city centres. "The cameras are clearly visible when they are worn and the instant playback facility means that officers can easily see again exactly who did what in public disorder situations, as well as showing the offenders themselves the poor level of their behaviour. "In many cases this will come as a wake up call and can help situations from deteriorating, especially if those involved know they are being filmed." CSO Merrick Liston, from Shropshire, said: "It takes a lot of worry off us - evidential situations where we need to write stuff down, depending on the situation at the time. "It records a lot of stuff that goes on, so it saves a lot of paperwork for us and again sometimes we might miss something, so it picks it up for us." Hereford and Worcester Sport, travel and more for Hereford and Worcester Licensing team to use head cams 10 Apr 07 | Sussex hunt four men after attack Balloonists head for Shropshire Free park and ride tackles cars e-mail 'hit' by spammers
