http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/edinburgh_and_east/6707877.stm | Edinburgh and East | Tesco union in strike stand-off GMT 15:57 union in strike stand-off The T&G union has confirmed they are to hold a second 24-hour strike A second strike has been called in the row over changes to working conditions for drivers based at Tesco's Livingston distribution depot. The Transport and General Workers' Union (T&G) say 150 drivers are to join the 24-hour strike next Tuesday. Tesco have strongly denied claims that drivers based in Livingston had been threatened with job losses if they did not sign a new contract. A Tesco spokesman has accused the union of "following their own agenda". Almost 150 Tesco delivery drivers went on strike for two days last week in a row over new contracts and plans to transfer the depot to premises 500m away. Tesco is used to getting its own way but the local community is incensed by the way they are being treated The Transport and General Workers' Union (T&G) claims drivers had been told they would lose their jobs if they did not sign a new contract, which they claimed includes worse working terms and conditions. The union says the new contracts will mean losses to the drivers of between £3,000 and £6,000, and derecognition of their union as the depot moves location. The T&G claim that drivers voted by 126 to 6 to strike in a ballot ,where more than nine out of 10 members took part. Tony Trench, regional industrial organiser for the T&G section of Unite, said the strike action would take place amidst growing local community support. He said: "Tesco is used to getting its own way but the local community is incensed by the way they are being treated. "Much of the support for the drivers is from their families and I'm delighted that a women's action committee has been formed." The union said drivers had been angered by a "provocative" letter received from Tesco instructing them not to come to work for seven days as a "cooling off period". Ron Webb, national secretary for transport in the T&G section of Unite, said the letter was outside his experience as a trade union official and questioned its legal status. We are investing £75m in the area and creating 1,000 jobs A spokesman for Tesco said that the claims of drivers losing £3,000 in pay were "complete, total nonsense", and challenged the union to find any driver who would lose this amount. He said that the union members had been sent a letter instigating a seven day cooling-off period, during which the drivers would receive full pay and some overtime payments. The Tesco spokesman said that the dispute was of no advantage to the drivers and that the T&G had created the dispute for its own agenda. He claimed that the previous week's strike had very little union support, with two-out-of-three T&G union stewards at Livingston not supporting the strike. He said that the Livingston depot was not being used as a testing ground for these terms and conditions: "These people have been offered guaranteed, protected terms and conditions. "The same conditions have already been implemented in four distribution sites across the UK, with complete union consultation and no industrial action." He added: "We are investing £75m in the area and creating 1,000 jobs." T&G Unite shop stewards will meet in London this Saturday to discuss the next stages of the national campaign, including talks on a national strike ballot. dispute enters second day 25 May 07 | Edinburgh and East Tesco lorry drivers go on strike 24 May 07 | Edinburgh and East Tesco drivers to stage walk-out 14 May 07 | Edinburgh and East Supermarket drivers set to strike 01 May 07 | Edinburgh and East Council critical of Tesco meeting 20 Mar 06 | Scotland Tesco to create jobs in £75m plan 14 Mar 06 | Scotland Union meets Tesco over job cuts 14 Mar 06 | Scotland Transport and General Workers Union EDINBURGH AND EAST STORIES Witness appeal after hit-and-run OAP billed for home's demolition Injured quad bike boy abandoned e-mail 'hit' by spammers
