http://news.bbc.co.uk/go/rss/-/1/hi/england/surrey/6706851.stm | Surrey | Thatcher strikes Falklands coin GMT 15:46 strikes Falklands coin The one-crown coin struck by Lady Thatcher bears a Britannia design Baroness Margaret Thatcher has struck a one-crown gold coin as part of a collection to mark 25 years since the liberation of the Falkland Islands. The former prime minister was at Pobjoy Mint, in Kingswood, Surrey, for the introduction of a commemorative set of coins which will become legal tender. It includes 50-pence pieces with a map of the Falkland Islands and a "yomper" - a soldier marching with a rucksack. Troops were sent there by Lady Thatcher when Argentina invaded in 1982. She dismissed advice from defence officials who feared that the islands, which are 8,000 miles from Britain, could not be retaken. The Argentinians surrendered after 74 days, but more than 900 lives were lost during that time. Some of the coins will become legal tender in the Falklands The South American country has continually claimed sovereignty over the British overseas territory since 1833. Speaking at Pobjoy Mint, Lady Thatcher, 81, said: "As prime minister I learnt that when government puts money into circulation, all you get is inflation. "But on this very special occasion, perhaps I can make an exception to this rule." The commemorative coins were commissioned by the Falkland Islands' government. All the schoolchildren on the islands will be given one of the 50-pence pieces. travel and more from the BBC website for Surrey and Sussex Argentina renews Falklands claim Thatcher remembers war dead UK 'regret' over Falklands dead Falklands war was right - Blair Falklands enemies meet at last From wool to fish - surviving in the South Atlantic Learning on a remote farm Images from capital Stanley Was invasion day marked? The Falkland Islands way Oil billions beckon Falklands The 1982 Falklands invasion, recapture and island life today 'The Falklands are Argentine' How BBC man scooped