http://news.bbc.co.uk/go/rss/-/1/hi/england/tees/6720233.stm BBC NEWS | England | Tees | Bird haven saved from drying out Skip to bbc.co.uk navigation Your news when you want it Also in the news Monday, 4 June 2007, 17:35 GMT 18:35 UK haven saved from drying out The park at Saltholme has been saved from drying out A Teesside nature reserve currently under construction has been saved from drying out after a firm donated water. More than 1,000 acres (400 hectares) of former industrial land on the north Tees at Saltholme is being transformed into a wild bird nature reserve. But the site was in danger of drying out until nearby chemical firm Sabic UK piped in several thousand cubic metres of water to combat dry weather. Already 30 pairs of lapwings, redshanks and snipes have moved to the site. A spokesman for the RSPB, which is helping to develop the site, said: "Wetland-loving birds such as lapwing and snipe were showing little signs of wanting to nest in the dry conditions. "However, thanks to some nifty lateral thinking, the RSPB has teamed up with local industry to bring Saltholme meadows back to life and the site is now teeming with nesting wetland birds. "A supply of water has been brought to the area thanks to the help of local company Sabic UK who are 'donating' the water - a by-product of their brine production management operations. "The water might otherwise have gone unused, but is now providing a lifeline for breeding birds." The nature reserve is due to open next year and is expected to attract 100,000 visitors a year. travel, webcams and more from the BBC website for Tees Landmark for nature reserve plan 02 Aug 06 | Tees Nature reserve manager appointed 14 Jan 06 | Tees Wild bird centre design unveiled 15 Oct 05 | Tees Land deal heralds nature reserve 30 May 05 | Tees Big Tees bird plan moves forward 17 Nov 04 | Science/Nature hope patient to stay home Crash driver 'knew of collision' Bird haven saved from drying out MOST POPULAR STORIES NOW Moroccan fami